canvas_summaries.ocr_text: VWD19 e tonal Union of Women Teacher 39. Gordon Square, W. 0. 1. Equal Pay for Equal Work in The Civil Service. The Question at Issue. One of the important questions which Members of Parliament have to face is the demand in the Civil Service for Equal Pay for Equal Work as between men and women. The House of Commons on two occasions affirmed the principle of Equal Pay in the Civil Service, first on May 19th, 1920, and again in August, 1921, but so far nothing has been done to put it into operation. The reason given by the Government for the failure to implement the promise contained in the Resolutions referred to above is that the expense involved is too great, but it should be noted that the demand now put forward is not for the immediate payment of large sums of money, but for the setting up of a Select Com mittee to consider and report upon the best means of giving effect to the principle accepted by the House of Commons. GO Cost . The demand for a Select Committee is based in part on the necessity for obtaining an authoritative statement as to the cost of applying the principle of Equal Pay. The question has never been impartially or adequately explored, and the estimates given from time to time by the Treasury have been both widely divergent and misleading.

canvas_summaries.ocr_text: Merits of the Case. Women are now employed on professional, adminis trative, executive, clerical, technical and other work in almost all Departments of State. They hold important and equally responsible positions with men, but generally at a lower rate of pay. Even in cases where the starting pay is equal, the increments are less and the maximum is considerably lower. The fact that women do equal work with men has been officially recognised: Departments, when reorgan ising their work, have decided the grade to which posts should belong irrespective of the sex of the official who would be subsequently appointed. Moreover, in a few instances in the Service, the salary scales of men and women are the same. Instances of Equal Pay Elsewhere. IN PARLIAMENT.- The two women appointed within recent years as Parliamentary Secretaries were appointed on the same salaries as their male predecessors, and women Members of Parliament receive the same salary as men Members of Parliament. IN THE PROFESSIONS .- Women Lawyers, Doctors, Accountants, and Journalists all receive the same remuneration as their men colleagues, and the Professors at the London, Birmingham, Edinburgh, and Manchester Universities are remunerated irrespective of sex. Who Supports the Demand? The principle has been approved by the House of Commons on two occasions without a division.
